Text The following were evaluated: clinical signs (twice daily), body weight (Days 1, 3, 7 and 10), food consumption (daily), hematology (at necropsy), serum chemistry (at necropsy), urinalysis (Day 3 or 10), toxicokinetics (Days 1 and 10), macroscopic observations at necropsy, organ weights and histopathology. There were no treatment related unscheduled deaths during the study. Treatment-related clinical signs were restricted to suspected dehydration and fur staining red. There was no apparent gender-related difference in systemic exposure (assessed by ) in this study: females appeared to have similar exposure compared to males. Tmax was observed between 2.0 and 8.0 hours for all genders, dose groups, and study days. Systemic exposure increased with increasing dose level for both males and females. T1/2 was prolonged with increasing dose level for both males and females. Exposure was similar on Day 10 compared with Day 1 for both males and females in all dose groups. There was no treatment related effect on organ weights (absolute and relative to body weight) following 3 or 10 days dose administration. Treated-related macroscopic and microscopic findings were seen in the kidney of rats given 200 mg/kg/day SAR377142. Macroscopically, pale discoloration of the medulla or corticomedullary junction was noted, this correlated with microscopically tubular degeneration/regeneration was observed in the outer medulla of both male and female rats given 200 mg/kg/day SAR377142 for 3 and 10 days with an higher incidence and severity noted after 10 days of treatment. INTRODUCTION The objectives of this study were to investigate the potential toxicity of SAR377142 during daily oral gavage to the rat for a minimum of 3 or 10 days. In addition, the toxicokinetic characteristics of SAR377142 were also determined. The dose levels were 0, 50 and 200 mg/kg/day. The doses were selected based on the results of a previous exploratory 2-week oral toxicity study performed in male and female Sprague-Dawley rats at 50, 200 and 600 mg/kg/day (DDO 0979, sanofi-aventis). In the latter study, all rats dosed at 600 mg/kg/day were found dead or euthanized prematurely on Day 5 following body weight loss and other clinical signs of hypomotility, ataxia, dyspnea, polyuria, skin redness and/or ptyalism. The dose of 200 mg/kg/day led to the premature demise of 3/12 rats (2 males and 1 female) on Day 14 or 15 and was associated with body weight loss and late onset clinical signs. The dose of 50 mg/kg/day was clinically well tolerated over 2 weeks, with only slight reductions in body weight gain and no compound-related clinical signs. In order to attain the study objectives (mainly induction of renal toxicity) without compromising animal health status and survival, the dosing duration was reduced from 15 to 10 days and the doses selected are 50 and 200 mg/kg/day. The Sprague Dawley rat is an accepted rodent species for use in toxicity studies and the oral route was selected since this is the intended route of administration in humans. The study was completed on the date appearing on the compliance statement page. EXPERIMENTAL PROCEDURES Test System Receipt A total of 66 male and 66 female Sprague Dawley rats were received from Vital River Lab Animal Co, Ltd on 17 Dec 2009. Subsequent to arrival, all animals were subjected to a general physical examination by a qualified member of the veterinary staff to ensure normal health status. With the exception of Animal Nos. 31M, 37M and 51M were noted fur staining red, which were assigned to the spare animal. The rest of animals were considered suitable for use. Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 13 Assignment to Treatment Groups 5 days prior to treatment, all animals were weighed and randomly assigned to treatment groups using a computer-based randomization procedure. Randomization was by stratification using body weight as the parameter. Males and females were randomized separately. The study design is detailed in Text Table 2 . Toxicokinetic animals were used for toxicokinetic evaluation only. Data relating to clinical examination and body weight collected from these animals were retained on file, but not reported. Text c Dose volume was 12.9mL/Kg, dose concentration was expressed as salt form. Animals in poor health or at the extremes of the body weight range were not assigned to groups. On Day 1 (24 Dec 2009), Animal No. 3013 swallowed the oral gavage tube during dose administration, the animal was replaced immediately with Animal No. 3025. The replaced animal was subject to gross pathological examination and tissue retention; results were retained on file, but not reported. Spare animals unassigned to treatment were released from the study without further examination. Analysis of Dose Formulations Dose formulations were determined to be stable for at least 10 days at 2-8Â°C and 4 hours at ambient temperature. The dose formulations were prepared by the test facility once prior to study start to confirm the suitability of the preparation method (Day -2). Homogeneity and concentration of this preparation were assessed. The formulation was sampled (5 mL) in triplicate from approximately the top, middle and bottom of the formulation. On Day 1, triplicate samples (5 mL/each) were taken from the top, middle and bottom of the preparation vessel, in addition to triplicate samples(5 mL/each) from the middle of Day 1 dosing containers following resuspension. The Day 8 preparation triplicate samples (5 mL/each) have been taken from the top, middle and bottom of the preparation vessel, in addition to triplicate samples(5 mL/each) from the middle of Day 10 dosing containers following resuspension. All formulations were stirred at least 30 minutes prior to sampling for analysis. The first two sets of samples were analyzed for concentration at Frontage Laboratories (Shanghai). The results were forwarded to the Study Director for inclusion in the study report. Retention samples that were not required for analysis were discarded upon confirmation of the analytical results. The report is present in Appendix 5. Administration of Test/Control Article Each rat was given a daily oral dose of vehicle or test article using a plastic gavage tube. Animals were treated at approximately the same time each day, 7 days a week for up to 10 days. The dosing volume was 12.9 mL/kg. Each actual volume administered was based on the most recent practical body weight of each animal. In addition, a detailed examination was performed at least once prior to the start of treatment and daily throughout the treatment period. With the exception of mortality, clinical signs data from toxicokinetic animals were retained on file, but not reported. Body Weights Individual body weights were measured for all animals on the day of randomization (retained on file, but not reported) Days 1, 3, 7 and 10. In addition, each main study animal was weighed (fasted) before scheduled necropsy. Individual body weight data for toxicokinetic animals were retained on file, but not reported. Food Consumption Food consumption (cage measurement) for all animals (excluding toxicokinetic animals) was measured once on the last week of the pre-treatment period and daily throughout the treatment period. Due to the Animal No. 3013 being replacement with Animal No. 3025, the daily food consumption was not recorded for cage 3012. Consequently, food consumption results were not recorded for Animal No's 3012 and 3025 on Day 2 (25 Dec 2009). Blood samples were collected from the abdominal aorta under isoflurane anesthesia. Urine samples were collected on wet ice on Day 4 or 11 from main study animals of interim or terminal termination placed in metabolism cages for an approximate 16-hours collection period, during which the animals were deprived of both food and water. A similar proportion of animals from each group and sex, as appropriate, were euthanized on any one day. In order to avoid autolytic change, a complete gross pathology examination of the carcass was performed as soon as possible after euthanasia of all main study animals. All scheduled necropsies were conducted under the supervision of a pathologist/necropsy specialist, and necropsy consisted of an external examination, including identification of all clinically recorded lesions, as well as a detailed internal examination. The carcasses of toxicokinetic animals euthanized by CO 2 asphyxiation were discarded without further examination. Skin dry (male: 2/5) and fur staining red (male: 1/5; female: 2/5) were noted for animals treated with 200 mg/kg/day SAR377142 for 3 days. Slight suspected dehydration was noted in male animals (4/10) dose with 200 mg/kg/day during the study with higher incidences observed on Day 11. Animal No. 3009 (200mg/kg/day) was noted to have slight dehydration on Days 8 to 11. Fur staining red was noted for animals in all groups, including controls, with a higher incidence for animals receiving 200 mg/kg/day (male: 4/10; female 7/10) during the 10 day treatment period. Fur staining red was also observed for both the concurrent control and animals given 200 mg/kg/day SAR377142 during 3 days treatment period. Incidental findings included but were not restricted to fur thin cover, fur wet, skin blue and skin scab. As incidences were noted in all treated groups, including controls, during the treatment period, they were therefore considered incidental. (Table 2, Table 3 , Appendix 12 and Appendix 13) Body Weights and Body weights gain There was a treatment related reduction in body weight noted for animals receiving 200 mg/kg/day SAR377142 throughout the study. This was due to the reduced body weight gain when compared to the concurrent control group. The reduction in bodyweight gain was dosage related in degree, and due to the magnitude (i.e.>10% for animals given 200 mg/kg/day) was considered to be adverse. The male animals treated with 50 mg/kg/day also had a slight reduction in body weight gain and body weight throughout 10 days treatment period when compared to the concurrent control. However, the reduction was less than that seen at 200 mg/kg/day and is considered to be non adverse. There were no treatment related effect on body weight gain for female at 50 mg/kg/day as group mean values were comparable to the concurrent control. Coincident with commencement of dosing a treatment related reduction in food consumption was observed for animals from all treated Groups. The reduction in average food consumption (Day 1 to 10) was dosage related in degree and correlated to some extent to the reduced bodyweight, with greater reduction seen for those animals receiving 200 mg/kg/day (male -16.2%, female -14.1%). At 50 mg/kg/day (male -3.4%, female +0.1%) this finding was also apparent although to a lesser degree when compared to concurrent control group. (Table 5 and Appendix 15) On Day 4, there was a minimal to mild increase in prothrombin time (PT) in females and males given 200 mg/kg/day. On Day 11, there was a mild increase in neutrophil (NEUT) in males at 200 mg/kg/day, (mainly due to Animal No. 3014 which also had an increase in FIB, but no direct correlation in pathology). There were minimal increases in red blood cell (RBC), haemoglobin (Hb) and hematocrit (Ht) of males given 200 mg/kg/day and females given â¥50 mg/kg/day, these changes correlated with the clinical finding of dehydration. There were minimal to mild dose-related increases in PT in males given 200 mg/kg/day and females given â¥50 mg/kg/day. (Table 6 and Appendix 16) On Day 4, there was no treatment-related change noted in serum chemistry parameters. Hematology Serum Chemistry On Day 11, there was a treatment-related increase noted in group mean urea nitrogen (+39%) in male animals treated with SAR377142 at 200 mg/kg/day. There was also an increase in 1/10 female at 200 mg/kg/day, when compared to the concurrent control group. In addition, Animal No. 3009 also had an increase in urea nitrogen (28.3 mg/dL) level when compared to the concurrent control group (11.2-18.0 mg/dL). There were no treatment-related effects noted for both males and females following 3 or10 days dose administration at 50 mg/kg/day. (Table 7 and Appendix 17) Urinalysis Treatment-related urinalysis findings included increases in urinary protein, glucose and urinary volume; traced occult blood; decrease in mean urinary PH; increase in bacteria and white blood cell in urine centrifuge sediment. Following 3 days dose administration, a notable increase in urinary volume was recorded for Animal No. 3005 (10 mL when compare to the concurrent control [3.6~6.6 mL]). In addition, the presence of glucose was noted for Animals 3004 and 3005 (5.5 mmol/L). Increased urine volume and decreased specific gravity were also noted in females at 200 mg/kg/day. For all animals treated at 200 mg/kg/day, an increase in urinary protein was observed when compared to concurrent control group. In addition, few to many increased numbers of bacteria and urine white blood cell (UWBC) in male treated with 200 mg/kg/day were also noted. In addition, a decrease in group mean urine pH was noted for animals receiving 200 mg/kg/day when compared to concurrent control group. Toxicokinetics (Appendix 6, Appendix 7 and Appendix 18) SAR377142 concentrations were below limit of quantitation in majority of the vehicle control group. Trace amount of SAR377142 were detected in the plasma samples from only 1 male rat in the control group on Day 10. However, that concentration was lower than 0.2% of the corresponding mean Day 10 plasma Cmax values in male rats at 50 mg/kg. There was no apparent gender-related difference in systemic exposure (assessed by Cmax and AUC (0-24)) in this study: females appeared to have similar exposure compared to males. On Day 1, Cmax values for females were 1.5 x and 0.99 x and AUC(0-24) values for females were 1.3 x and 1.1 x compared to males for the 50 and 200 mg/kg/day dose groups, respectively. On Day 10, Cmax values for females were 1.4 x and 1.3 x and AUC(0-24) values for females were 1.3 x and 1.4 x compared to males for the 50 and 200 mg/kg/day dose groups, respectively. For both males and females, Tmax on Day 1 and Day 10 was observed at 4 hours for the 50 mg/kg/day dose groups. For 200 mg/kg/day dose groups, Tmax of both males and females was observed at 4 hours on Day 1 and 8 hour versus 2 h for males and females on Day 10, respectively. For both males and females, systemic exposure increased with increasing dose. For males on Day 1, the mean Cmax and AUC(0-24) increased by 3.8 x and 4.4 x, respectively, with a 4 x increase in dose (from 50 to 200 mg/kg/day). On Day 10, the mean Cmax and AUC(0-24) increased by 3.1 x and 3.7 x, respectively, with a 4 x increase in dose (from 50 to 200 mg/kg/day). For females on Day 1, the mean Cmax and AUC(0-24) increased by 2.5 x and 3.7 x, respectively, with a 4 x increase in dose (from 50 to 200 mg/kg/day). On Day 10, the mean Cmax and AUC(0-24) increased by 3.0 x and 4.1 x, respectively, with a 4 x increase in dose (from 50 to 200 mg/kg/day). For males on Day 1 and Day 10, T1/2 increased by 2.1 x and 1.5 x with a 4 x increase in dose (from 50 to 200 mg/kg/day). For females on Day 1 and Day 10, T1/2 increased by 4.0 x and 3.7 x with a 4 x increase in dose (from 50 to 200 mg/kg/day). For both males and females, exposure was similar on Day 10 compared to Day 1. For males on Day 10, Cmax values were 1.0 x and 0.82 x and AUC(0-24) values were 0.97 x and 0.82 x compared to Day 1 for the 50 and 200 mg/kg/day dose groups, respectively. (Table 8, Table 9 , Appendix 19 and Appendix 20) Organ Weights There were no test article-related effects were noted on organ weights (absolute and relative to body weight) of male and female rats dosed with SAR377142 daily for either 3 or 10 days at dose level up to 200 mg/kg. All organ weight differences noted on Day 4 and 11, including those that reached statistical significance, were considered to be within expected biological variation seen in rats of this age. (Table 10 , Appendix 8, Appendix 9 and Appendix 21) Gross Pathology On Day 4 no significant macroscopic changes were observed in male and female rats dosed daily with SAR377142 for 3 days. On Day 11 macroscopic finding considered to be related to the administration of SAR377142 was seen in the kidney of both male and female rats given SAR377142 daily for 10 days. Pale discoloration of the medulla or corticomedullary junction was observed in 1/10 male and 7/10 female rats at 200 mg/kg/day. This finding correlated microscopically with medullary tubular degeneration/regeneration. All other gross findings observed in various organs and tissues of rats euthanized on Day 4 and 11 were considered to be agonal or incidental in origin. Property of the sanofi-aventis group -strictly confidential Page 32 6.12. Histopathology (Table 11 , Appendix 9 and Appendix 21) On Day 4 histopathological changes considered to be SAR377142-related were observed in the kidney. Minimal tubular degeneration/regeneration was observed in the outer medulla of 4/5 male and 1/5 female rats at 200 mg/kg/day. On Day 11 histopathological changes considered to be SAR377142-related were observed in the kidney. Minimal to marked tubular degeneration/necrosis was observed in the outer medulla of all male and female rats at 200 mg/kg/day. Tubular degeneration/regeneration was morphologically comparable in both study phases and located primarily in the inner stripe of the outer medulla, extending occasionally in the outer stripe of the outer medulla. The tubules were lined by enlarged basophilic, often vacuolated, epithelial cells showing enlarged irregular vesicular nuclei and bulging into the tubule lumen. These changes were associated with individual tubular cell necrosis, the presence of necrotic cellular debris in tubular lumen, low number of mitotic figures interpreted as early evidence of regeneration, tubular dilatation and mononuclear cell infiltration. An increase in incidence and severity of tubular degeneration/regeneration was noted with longer duration of treatment. All other microscopic findings seen in kidney and various organs and tissues were considered to be agonal, incidental or related to the experimental procedure and were of no toxicological significance. CONCLUSION In conclusion, the administration of SAR377142 by daily oral gavage for 3 or 10 days at dose levels of 0, 50 mg/kg/day and 200 mg/kg/day resulted in clinical signs of dehydration and fur staining red, adverse reductions in body weight gain with associated reduced food consumption, minor hematology (prolonged PT), biochemical (increased BUN), significant urinalysis changes (increased urinary protein and occult blood, glycosuria and polyuria), with associated macroscopic (pale discolouration in medulla or corticomedullary junction) and microscopic changes(tubular degeneration/regeneration in the outer medulla) in the kidney of rats treated with 200 mg/kg/day SAR377142. Consequently, the no-adverse-effect-level was considered to be 50 mg/kg/day in this study. 10 N.A.D. 10 - 10 ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- GENERAL SUMMARY Purpose The objectives of this study are to investigate the potential toxicity of SAR377142 during daily oral gavage to the rat for a minimum of 3 or 10 days. In addition, the toxicokinetic characteristics of SAR377142 will be determined. REASON FOR CHOICE OF TEST SYSTEM The rat is a standard rodent species for use in oral gavage toxicity studies. REASON FOR CHOICE OF ROUTE OF ADMINISTRATION The oral route has been selected since this is the intended route of administration in humans. REASON FOR DOSE LEVEL SELECTION The doses were selected based on the results of a previous exploratory 2-week oral toxicity study performed in male and female Sprague-Dawley rats at 50, 200 and 600 mg/kg/day (DDO 0979, sanofi-aventis). In the latter study, all rats dosed at 600 mg/kg/day were found dead or euthanized prematurely on Day 5 following body weight loss and other clinical signs of hypomotility, ataxia, dyspnea, polyuria, skin redness and/or ptyalism. The dose of 200 mg/kg/day led to the premature demise of 3/12 rats (2 males and 1 female) on Day 14 or 15 and was associated with body weight loss and late onset clinical signs. The dose of 50 mg/kg/day was clinically well tolerated over 2 weeks, with only slight reductions in body weight gain and no compound-related clinical signs. In order to attain the study objectives (mainly induction of renal toxicity) without compromising animal health status and survival, the dosing duration will be reduced from 15 to 10 days and the doses selected are 50 and 200 mg/kg/day. Main study: 5 rats/sex/group1 and 3 (interim termination), 10 rats/sex/group (terminal termination); toxicokinetic study: 9 rats/sex/treatment group and 3 rats/sex/control group, plus 5 rat/sex of spares from the same batch of animals ordered for the study. PARTICIPATING PERSONNEL Study Director Actual age, weight, acclimation period and number of animals received will be indicated in the study report. Following arrival, each animal will be given a general physical examination by the veterinarian to assess health status. Housing On arrival, animals will be group housed (up to 3 animals of the same sex and same dosing group together) in solid bottom cages, with bedding, equipped with an automatic watering valve unless deemed inappropriate by the Study Director and/or Clinical Veterinarian. The environmental enrichment program will be in accordance with the appropriate SOP. Each cage will be clearly labeled with a color-coded cage card indicating project, group, animal numbers and sex. Cages will be arranged on the racks in group order. Where possible, control group animals will be housed on a separate rack from the test article treated animals. Each animal will be uniquely identified using the AIMS Â® tail tattoo system or other permanent marker. If required, animals may be temporarily identified using indelible ink. Maximum allowable concentrations of contaminants in the diet (e.g., heavy metals, aflatoxin, organophosphate, chlorinated hydrocarbons, PCBs) are controlled and routinely analyzed by the manufacturers. The results of the analysis are reviewed by the attending veterinary and retained at PCS-SHG. Municipal tap water which has been softened, purified by reverse osmosis and exposed to ultraviolet light will be freely available (except during designated procedures). Periodic analysis of the water is subcontracted to management authorized analytical laboratories which are audited by the Quality Assurance department of PCS-SHG. The analytical results are reviewed by the attending veterinary and retained in the archives of PCS-SHG. It is considered that there are no known contaminants in the dietary materials that could interfere with the objectives of the study. Assignment to Groups A minimum acclimation period of 7 days will be allowed between animal receipt and the start of treatment in order to accustom the animals to the laboratory environment. Prior to treatment initiation, all animals will be weighed and assigned to treatment groups using a randomization procedure. Randomization is by stratification using body weight as the parameter. Animals in poor health or at extremes of body weight range will not be assigned to groups. Prior to the initiation of dosing, any assigned animals considered unsuitable for use in the study will be replaced by spare animals obtained from the same shipment and maintained under the same environmental conditions. Males and females of the interim or terminal termination of main study will be separated into four replicates for dosing. Replicate 1 and 3 will contain all males and replicate 2 and 4 all females. Dosing for each sex will commence on consecutive days to allow adequate time for necropsy scheduling. If a dataset has less than three non-missing values in each group, then the following inferential data analysis will not be done. No inferential data analysis will be conducted on group-housed food consumption and water consumption. Whenever there are more than two groups, the homogeneity of the group variances will be evaluated using the Levene test at the 0.05 significance level. If differences between group variances are not found to be significant (p > 0.05), then a parametric one-way analysis of variance (ANOVA) will be performed. When significant differences among the means are indicated by the overall ANOVA F-test (p â¤ 0.05), the Dunnett test will be used to perform the group mean comparisons between the control group and each treated group. If Levene's test indicates heterogeneous group variances (p â¤ 0.05), then the non-parametric Kruskal-Wallis test will be used to compare all considered groups. When the Kruskal-Wallis test is significant (p â¤ 0.05), the Dunn test will be used to perform the pairwise group comparisons of interest (the same as for the Dunnett mentioned in the previous paragraph). Whenever there are only two groups to compare, the Levene test will be performed as described above but a two-sample t-test will replace the one-way ANOVA, a Wilcoxon rank-sum test will be performed instead of the Kruskal-Wallis and, no Dunnett or Dunn tests will be performed. Each pairwise group comparisons of interest will be conducted via a two-sided test at the 5% significance level. Significant results will be reported as either p â¤ 0.001, p â¤ 0.01 or p â¤ 0.05, where p represents the observed probability. (Table 8, Table 9 , Appendix 19 and Appendix 20) Organ Weights Day 4 No test article-related effects were noted on organ weights (absolute and relative to body weight) of male and female rats dosed with SAR377142 daily for 3 days. (Table 10 and Appendix 21) Macroscopic Findings Day 4 No significant macroscopic changes were observed in male and female rats dosed daily with SAR377142 for 3 days. Day 11 Macroscopic finding considered to be related to the administration of SAR377142 was seen in the kidney of both male and female rats given SAR377142 daily for 10 days. Pale discoloration of the medulla or corticomedullary junction was observed in 1/10 male and 7/10 female rats at 200 mg/kg/day. This finding correlated microscopically with medullary tubular degeneration/regeneration. All other gross findings observed in various organs and tissues of rats euthanized on Day 4 and 11 were considered to be agonal or incidental in origin. Histopathological changes considered to be SAR377142-related were observed in the kidney. Minimal tubular degeneration/regeneration was observed in the outer medulla of 4/5 male and 1/5 female rats at 200 mg/kg/day. Day 11 Histopathological changes considered to be SAR377142-related were observed in the kidney. Minimal to marked tubular degeneration/regeneration was observed in the outer medulla of all male and female rats at 200 mg/kg/day. Tubular degeneration/regeneration was morphologically comparable in both study phases and located primarily in the inner stripe of the outer medulla, extending occasionally in the outer stripe of the outer medulla. The tubules were lined by enlarged basophilic, often vacuolated, epithelial cells showing enlarged irregular vesicular nuclei and bulging into the tubule lumen. These changes were associated with individual tubular cell necrosis, the presence of necrotic cellular debris in tubular lumen, low number of mitotic figures interpreted as early evidence of regeneration, tubular dilatation and mononuclear cell infiltration. An increase in incidence and severity of tubular degeneration/regeneration was noted with longer duration of treatment. All other microscopic findings seen in the kidney and various organs and tissues were considered to be agonal, incidental or related to the experimental procedure and were of no toxicological
